Wash and dry all produce. Thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced), keeping greens and whites separate. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Core and seed @poblano pepper{1}(seeded and cut into ½-inch squares), then cut into ½-inch squares. Drain and rinse @kidney beans{1%14oz can}(drained and rinsed).

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and @Mexican spice blend{1%tablespoon}, breaking up meat into pieces. Cook, stirring occasionally, until crisped at the edges and no longer pink, ~{4-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and set aside.

Add a drizzle of oil, scallion whites, poblano, and garlic to pan. Cook, tossing, until lightly browned and softened, about ~{5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir @chicken stock concentrate{1%unit}, kidney beans, @crushed tomatoes{1%14oz can}, and @water{1/2%cup} into pan. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and reduce to a simmer. Let bubble until slightly thickened, about ~{5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Return pork and any drippings to pan, stirring to combine. Simmer until saucy and very thick, about ~{5%minutes} longer.

Divide chili between #bowls{}. Sprinkle with @cheddar cheese{1/2%cup} and dollop with @sour cream{4%tablespoon}. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.

> It doesn't matter whether the weather's hot or cold where you are—it's chili season! In this version, we're keeping things simmering with ground pork, kidney beans, poblano pepper, and our Mexican spice blend, which has just the right amount of smoky heat. It's mild enough for anyone to gobble up, but with plenty of flavor. Just break out the hot sauce if you like it scorching!